csrf=vEtLGPaoHg8TEF7QfGVTdZvUno68fQw9&name=asd&email=asdv%40asd.hu&subject=asdas&message=asdas

I guess the email parameter will be the vulnerable so check it with ||sleep+10||...and if its sleeping for 10 secs, its vulnerable. And as we can see, it is.
Lets check it with ||whoami|| amybe we will get a response, but we dont. 
From the lab description we know that there is a writable folder: /var/www/images/ (which means we can write to a txt file into it with our results) so if we modify our payload to ||whoami+>+/var/www/images/results.txt||
It will create a txt file on the server with our result. But how we can check our file? Is it even exists?
So if you check the main site's source code, you will see that the site load a lot of pictures from this directory (this is the default directory to the images) like this:
                       <div>
                            <img src="/image?filename=18.jpg">
                            <h3>

all we have to do is copy this into the url, change the filename to results.txt, and there is our whoami...:
https://0a3300930436734c8299b20b00a300bd.web-security-academy.net//image?filename=results.txt

